<p>The text in the Guide is incorrect. Section 664A (1) (d) of the Act states that the period is 'for more than four weeks'.</p>
<h2 id="2may1996">Update 629G # Date 2 May 1996</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - 1) Activity test exemption - Jury duty. 2) No further transfers to sickness allowance. See guidelines 12.170 to 12.171 and 12.190 to 12.196.</p>
<p>1) Customers on JSA/NSA can be exempt from the activity test to a maximum of 13 weeks if they are selected to sit on a jury, ie empanelled.</p>
<p>2) Customers on JSA/NSA will not be exempt from the activity test if they are able to work eight hours per week or more.</p>
<h2 id="18april1996">Update 627G # Date 18 April 1996</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - No further transfers to sickness allowance. See guidelines 12.7400, 12.7500 to 12.7507 and 12.7600 to 12.7612.</p>
<p>1) Ordinary waiting period - severe financial hardship - incapacitated customers.</p>
<p>2) Liquid assets waiting period-incapacitated customers and members of a couple.</p>
<p>3) Education leavers waiting period - incapacitated customers.</p>
<h2>Update 626G # Date 18 April 1996</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - No further transfers to sickness allowance. See guidelines 12.6000 to 12.7003.</p>
<p>Provisional commencement day, waiting and deferment periods for customers who are exempt from the activity test because of an incapacity.</p>
<h2>Update 625G # Date 18 April 1996</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 42 - PORTABILITY AND COMPARABLE FOREIGN PAYMENTS - Portability of partner allowance and parenting allowance to New Zealand. See guidelines 42.170 and 42.173.</p>
<p>From 1/1/96 Partner allowance and parenting allowance with New Zealand are now portable for limited periods during temporary absences from Australia.</p>
<h2>Update 624G # Date 18 April 1996</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 42 - PORTABILITY AND COMPARABLE FOREIGN PAYMENTS - Portability for former residents. See guideline 42.121.</p>
